[4mROGUE[24m(6)                          Games Manual                          [4mROGUE[24m(6)

[1mNAME[0m
     rogue - Exploring The Dungeons of Doom - version 5.4.5

[1mSYNOPSIS[0m
     [1m@PROGRAM@ [22m[ [1m-s [22m[ [4mscore_flle[24m ] ] [ [1m-d [22m] [ [1m-V [22m] [ [1m-r [22m] [ [4msave_file[24m ]

[1mDESCRIPTION[0m
     [4mRogue[24m  is a computer fantasy game with a new twist.  It is CRT oriented and
     the object of the game is to survive the attacks of  various  monsters  and
     get  a lot of gold, rather than the puzzle solving orientation of most com-
     puter fantasy games.

     To get started you really only need to know two commands.   The  command  [1m?[0m
     will give you a list of the available commands and the command [1m/ [22mwill iden-
     tify the things you see on the screen.

     To  win  the game (as opposed to merely playing to beat other people's high
     scores) you must locate the Amulet of Yendor which is somewhere  below  the
     20th level of the dungeon and get it out.  Nobody has achieved this yet and
     if somebody does, they will probably go down in history as a hero among he-
     roes.

     When the game ends, either by your death, when you quit, or if you (by some
     miracle) manage to win, [4mrogue[24m will give you a list of the top scorers.  The
     scoring  is  based  entirely  upon  how  much gold you get.  There is a 10%
     penalty for getting yourself killed.

     If [4msave_file[24m is specified, rogue will be restored from the specified  saved
     game  file.  If the [1m-r [22moption is used, the save game file is presumed to be
     the default.

     The [1m-s [22moption will print out the list of  scores  from  the  default  score
     file.

     The  [1m-s [22mscore_file  option will print out the list of scores from the given
     [4mscore_file[24m.

     The [1m-d [22moption will kill you and try to add you to the score file.

     The [1m-V [22mwill print the rogue version, release date, and then exit.

     For more detailed directions, read  the  [1mREADME.md  [22mfile  of  the  rogue5.4
     GitHub repo:

          [4mhttps://github.com/lcn2/rogue5.4#rogue-54[0m

[1mOPTIONS[0m
     The [1mrogue [22mgame options may be displayed and changed by using the [1mo [22mcommand.

     The option names are:

     [1mterse / noterse[0m

            Useful  for those who are tired of the sometimes lengthy messages of
            rogue.

            This is a useful option to enable when playing  on  an  historically
            slow terminal.

            Default: [1mnoterse[0m

            Recommendation: [1mnoterse[0m

     [1mflush / noflush[0m

            If  this option is set, typeahead is thrown away after each round of
            battle.

            This is useful for those who type far ahead, and then watch in  dis-
            may as a Bat kills them.

            Default: [1mnoflush[0m

            Recommendation: [1mflush[0m

     [1mjump / nojump[0m

            If this option is set, running moves will not be displayed until you
            reach the end of the move.

            This  is  a  useful option to enable when playing on an historically
            slow terminal.

            Default: [1mnojump[0m

            Recommendation: [1mjump[0m

     [1mseefloor / noseefloor[0m

            Display the floor around you on the screen as you move through  dark
            rooms.

            This  is  a useful option to disable when playing on an historically
            slow terminal.

            Default: [1mseefloor[0m

            Recommendation: [1mseefloor[0m

     [1mpassgo / nopassgo[0m

            Follow turnings in passageways.  If you run in a passage and you run
            into stone or a wall, rogue will see if it can turn to the right  or
            left.  If it can only turn one way, it will turn that way. If it can
            turn either or neither, it will stop.

            This  algorithm can sometimes lead to slightly confusing occurrences
            to some people, which is why it defaults to false.

            Default: [1mnopassgo[0m

            Recommendation: [1mpassgo[0m

     [1mtombstone / notombstone[0m

            Print out the tombstone at the end if you get killed.

            This is a useful option to disable when playing on  an  historically
            slow terminal.

            Default: [1mtombstone[0m

            Recommendation: [1mtombstone[0m

     [1minven[22m=style

            Set the inventory style to one of: [1moverwrite[22m, [1mslow[22m, or [1mclear[22m.

            With  [1moverwrite[22m,  the  top lines of the map are overwritten with the
            list when inventory is requested, or when "Which item do you wish to
            ...?" questions are answered with a [1m* [22m(asterisk).  However,  if  the
            list is longer than a screenful, the screen is cleared.

            With  [1mslow[22m, lists are displayed one item at a time on the top of the
            screen.

            With [1mclear[22m, the screen is cleared, the list is displayed,  and  then
            the dungeon level is re-displayed.

            Default: [1mclear[0m

            Recommendation: [1moverwrite[0m

     [1mname[22m=rogue-name

            This  is the name of your character, as displayed in the rogue score
            file.

            Default: [1m<<your account name>>[0m

            Recommendation: [1m<<leave as default>>[0m

     [1mfruit[22m=fruit-name

            This should hold the name of a fruit that you enjoy eating.   It  is
            basically a whimsy that rogue uses in a couple of places.

            Default: [1mslime-mold[0m

            Recommendation: [1mapple[0m

     [1mfile[22m=rogue-save-path

            The default file name for saving the game.

            Default: [1m~/.rogue.save[0m

            Recommendation: [1m<<leave as default>>[0m

     [1mscore[22m=rogue-score-path

            The path of the rogue score file.

            [1mIMPORTANT  NOTE:  [22mChanging  the  rogue  score file path without also
            changing the rogue lock file path is [1mNOT [22ma good idea.

            Default: [1m~/.rogue.scr[0m

            Recommendation: [1m<<leave as default>>[0m

     [1mlock[22m=rogue-lock-path

            The rogue lock file used to protect the rogue score file.

            [1mIMPORTANT NOTE: [22mChanging the  rogue  lock  file  path  without  also
            changing the rogue score file path is [1mNOT [22ma good idea.

            Default: [1m~/.rogue.lck[0m

            Recommendation: [1m<<leave as default>>[0m

[1mENVIRONMENT[0m
     The following environment variables affect the execution of [1m$ROGUEOPTS[22m: The
     [1m$ROGUEOPTS [22menvironment variable may be used to change the [1mrogue [22mat startup,
     rather than having to use the [1mo [22mcommand each time you play.

     The  [1m$ROGUEOPTS  [22menvironment variable would be a string that is a series of
     comma separated values, with booleans being  stated  as  "name"  (true)  or
     "noname"  (false), and strings being "name=....", with the string being de-
     fined up to a comma or the end of the entire option string.

     As an example, here is a recommended [1m$ROGUEOPTS [22menvironment value to set in
     your environment:

          export     ROGUEOPTS="noterse,flush,jump,seefloor,passgo,tombstone,in-
          ven=overwrite,fruit=apple"

     If  the  [1m$ROGUEOPTS  [22menvironment value is missing or empty, the default op-
     tions will be used.  Unknown options are silently ignored.

     To assist in the debugging of [1mrogomatic, [22mif  the  name  of  your  character
     (i.e.,  [1mrogue-name[22m)  starts with [1mrogo- [22mwhen [1mrogue [22mstarts, then the environ-
     ment variable [1m$ROGOSEED [22mmay be used to set the rogue dungeon number.

     The [1mv [22mrogue command, in when printing the rogue version, and release  date,
     also prints the rogue dungeon number.

     [1mNOTE[22m:  Changing the [1mrogue-name [22mwith the [1mo [22mcommand does [1mNOT [22mst in the debug-
     ging of [1mrogomatic [22mas the [1mrogue-name [22mmust be set, via  the  above  mentioned
     [1m$ROGUEOPTS [22menvironment variable method [1mBEFORE rogue [22mstarts.  For example:

          ROGUEOPTS="name=rogo-bot" ROGOSEED=1227897957 rogue

     See  the [1mrogomatic[22m(6) man page for how rogue dungeon seed debugging is per-
     formed by [1mrogomatic[22m.

[1mFILES[0m
     [1mLock File [22m- @LOCKFILE@

            The rogue lock file is a zero-length file that must be  writable  by
            the  user.  It is used to help prevent multiple processes on the lo-
            cal machine from writing to the rogue score file at the same time.

            If the rogue lock file does not exist, the lock file will be created
            when updating the rogue score file.

     [1mSave file [22m- @SAVEFILE@

            The rogue save file is created whenever you use  the  [1mS  [22mcommand  to
            save the game, or if certain signals are successfully caught and the
            "auto save" action is successfully completed.

            A  rogue  save file is likely, but is not guaranteed to restore in a
            different system.  Among the diverse reasons a restore on a  differ-
            ent system might fail are CPU architecture differences, and the whim
            of the C compiler.

            If  the  rogue  save  file does not exist, it will be created when a
            game is saved.

     [1mScore File [22m- @SCOREFILE@

            The rogue score file contains the top rogue games, in terms of  gold
            collected.  By default, 10 rogue score are saved.

            The rogue score file must be writable by the user.

            The  length  of  the rogue score file is usually 112 bytes per score
            slot, so the default rogue score file size is 1120 bytes.

            Unlike the BSD rogue game on the Vax, rogue keeps track of top rogue
            scores, no matter how they were played, and no matter  if  they  won
            the game or not.

            If the rogue score file does not exist, [1mrogue [22mwill create it.

            If the rogue score file is corrupted, or the format is too old, then
            an  error  message  will  be displayed advising that the rogue score
            file be removed.

            If you enter into [1mwizard mode [22mat any time during the game, then your
            score will [1mNOT [22mbe recorded in the rogue score file, even if you turn
            off [1mwizard mode [22mduring the game.

[1mSOURCE CODE[0m
     The source code for rogue version 5.4.5 is available at:

          [4mhttps://github.com/lcn2/rogue5.4[0m

     in the form of a GitHub repo.

     The above GitHub repo  is  maintained  by:  [1mLandon Curt Noll  [22m(GitHub  user
     @lcn2: [4mhttps://github.com/lcn2[24m).

     The  port  to ISO C 2017 with GNU extensions, the port to various platforms
     such as NetBSD, Linux, and Cygwin, and many  rogue  bug  fixes  applied  to
     rogue  version  5.4.5 were made by Landon Curt Noll (chongo), and Anthony C
     Howe (SirWumpus).

     [1mBONUS[22m: The historic [1mwizard mode password [22mmay be found in a source code com-
     ment about a defined symbol in the [4mrogue.h[24m header file.  In other words, as
     the expression goes: [1mRTFS [22m([4mhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RTFS[24m) :-).

     For more information on [1mwizard mode[22m, see the [1mwizard mode [22mspoiler text at:

          [4mgithub.com/lcn2/rogue5.4#wizard-mode-spoilers[0m

[1mVERSION 5.4.5[0m
     The rogue version was changed from 5.4.4 to 5.4.5 to help distinguish  this
     code from various buggy 5.4.4 code.

     Rogue version 5.4.5 plays like the original Vax binary that was distributed
     on the BSD 4.3 Reno tapes.

     In  addition to a port to ISO C 2017 with GNU extensions, this version con-
     tains a fair number of significant bug fixes to help avoid the game  crash-
     ing.

     For a general overview of code improvements, see:

          [4mhttps://github.com/lcn2/rogue5.4#why-yet-another-rouge-repo[0m

     [1mIMPORTANT NOTE  :  [22mThis code is [1mNOT the so-called [4m[22mPublic[24m [4mdomain[24m [4mrogue[24m [1mrogue[0m
     [1mgame that distributions such as NetBSD imported from 386BSD.  [22mThat  "[4mPublic[0m
     [4mdomain[24m [4mrogue[24m" was an attempt to reverse engineer the original game found on
     the  BSD  distribution  tapes,  and  as such the game play differs from the
     original game in a number of ways.  Rogue version 5.4.5, thankfully, is [1mNOT[0m
     compatible with the NetBSD rogue.

